description: From Middle English frogge, from Old English frogga, frocga (“frog”), from Proto-West Germanic *froggō (“frog”).
Possibly related to Saterland Frisian Poage (“frog”), German Low German Pogg, Pogge (“frog”).

entries.meaning: Any of a class of small tailless amphibians of the order Anura that typically hop.
(music) The part of a violin bow (or that of other similar string instruments such as the viola, cello and contrabass) located at the end held by the player, to which the horsehair is attached.
(Cockney rhyming slang) Road. Shorter, more common form of frog and toad.
The depression in the upper face of a pressed or handmade clay brick.
An organ on the bottom of a horse’s hoof that assists in the circulation of blood.
(rail transport) The part of a railway switch or turnout where the running-rails cross (from the resemblance to the frog in a horse’s hoof).
(fishing) A type of fishing lure that resembles a frog.
(politics, slang, derogatory, Malaysia) defector: a politician who simply switches between different political parties.

entries.meaning: (transitive, biology) To use a pronged plater to transfer (cells) to another plate.

description: From frog legs, stereotypical food of the French. Compare French rosbif (“English person”), from roast beef, corresponding term for the English, likewise based on stereotypical food; and Kraut for Germans.

entries.meaning: (Canada, offensive) A French-speaking person from Quebec.

description: Unknown. Possibly borrowed from Portuguese froco (“flock”), from Latin floccus (“flock”).

entries.meaning: A leather or fabric loop used to attach a sword or bayonet, or its scabbard, to a waist or shoulder belt.
An ornate fastener for clothing consisting of an oblong button (covered with netted thread), toggle, or knot, that fits through a loop.

description: Supposedly from ribbit (“sound made by a frog”) sounding similar to "rip it".
